Definition of Success

In this section, we analyze the characteristics of clients according to their definition of success. Overall, we collect information about the following definitions of personal and business success:

Personal

  1. Business: A successful person is defined by its businessâ success.
  2. Household: A successful person is defined by stability in their household/family.
  3. Community: A successful person is defined by their contribution to the community.

Business

  1. Growth: A successful business is defined by its economic growth.
  2. Stability: A successful business is defined by financial stability and the fact that it can provide to their household.
  3. Community: A successful business is defined by their contribution to the community through positive changes or employment.

The objective is to characterize clients according to their definitions of success, both by comparing characteristics between clients, but also identifying in a data-driven way different clusters of individuals according to their characteristics, especially regarding their beliefs about success.

Personal definition of success

The following tables characterizes the attitudes of the previous groups regarding success at a personal level, in addition to general situation of the business and demographic characteristics. First, we analyze customers that either donât have a business anymore or declare to have never had a business (N = 287) against those that currently own a business (N = 1833). The following plot shows that for those that no longer have a business, their main focus is on their household, while for clients who currently have a business their definition of personal success is tightly linked to that business.

Figure 1. Definition of personal success by whether clients currently have a business or not

In the following analysis we only focus on people who currently have a business. Unsurprisingly, clients that tie personal success to business growth, have both higher initial amounts for loans, as well as business surplus. They also have slightly lower levels of risk aversion and loss aversion, and are willing to invest more in their business. These type of clients are also more ambitious with respect to their business, and have overall higher growth. Finally, they have higher educational levels than their counterparts.

Identifying optimal clusters

We would also like to know whether the beliefs and/or characteristics of the clients can be grouped in a data-driven way, so we can identify the optimal number of groups or clusters within our data. For this, we conduct a K-means cluster analysis, an unsupervised machine learning method to find the optimal number of clusters based on a set of characteristics. In this case, we provide the models with the attitudes towards success, demographic characteristics, information about their business and business practices, to see whether there are significant differences between definitions of success according to these groups.

The following figure shows the optimal numbers of clusters obtained using K-means:

Figure 3. Number of optimal clusters using Kmeans

Figure 4. Definition of personal success by clusters

Figure 5. Definition of personal success by clusters

Comparing these 4 optimal clusters in terms of definition of success, we note that most clusters have a similar distribution of personal definition of success, though cluster 5 appears to be the one with a higher proportion of business-oriented definition of personal success. In terms of the definition of success for businesses, cluster 2 appears to be highly oriented towards growth, while cluster 1, 5, and 6, much more oriented towards household stability. Cluster 4 in this case also stands out for being more focused on growth compared to the other groups.

  • Cluster 1: Household stability
  • Cluster 2: Business
  • Cluster 3-4: Equal distribution
  • Cluster 5-6: Business/stability

The following tables now show the differences in other characteristics between these four optimal clusters:

Figure 6. Clusters based on two main dimensions of the data

Not surprisingly, cluster 2 outperforms the other clusters in terms of loan metrics: This group has higher loan amounts and higher surplus. Additionally, they have higher expectations for their business. On the opposite end, cluster 6 appears to be the one with lower business performance.

Finally, we compare business characteristics across gender, as well as business practices. The following table shows that female clients have lower performance in terms of reported sales and number of workers, but also overall, they report being less proactive in terms of positive business practices, such as comparing prices or checking with the competition. The lack of desirable business practices could also be tied to the fact that women are not the main breadwinner in our sample.
